Data Wrangling in RStudio and Tableau Prep

by Jose Velazquez

Introduction

In this project I will use a single excel file to perform data wrangling and cleaning on RStudio and Tableau Prep side-by-side, identifying key differences in the process.

The name of the file is “bc-stats_2018-new-homes-data_tosend.xlsx”

Data Exploration

Listing the sheet names in the file and assigning easier names to each one.

housing <- "bc-stats_2018-new-homes-data_tosend.xlsx"

The file has a multi header that makes it difficult to assign the column names. It also has “*” instead of NAs. To fix this I will only read a range from the sheet and assign column names and types.

# For Single Detached sheet
single_detached <-
  read_excel(
    housing,
    sheet = "Single Detached",
    range = "B5:E164",
    col_names = c("community", "2016", "2017", "2018"),
    col_types = c("guess", "numeric", "numeric", "numeric"),
    na = "*"
  )

Tidy data

Making a tidy structure to work with. Because the 3 sheets share the same format, I will not drop the NA values yet.

single_detached_long <- single_detached %>%
  pivot_longer(-community, 
               names_to = "year", 
               values_to = "single")

Now in Tableau Prep

Pivot long:

Copying the process for the other sheets:

Joining tables

Joining the three tables, creating a single table that contains all of the information that was previously stored in three separate sheets.

new_homes_bc <- 
single_detached_long %>% 
  left_join(multi_unit_long, by = c("community", "year")) %>% 
  left_join(purpose_rental_long, by = c("community", "year")) 

new_homes_bc
## # A tibble: 480 x 5

Sending the processed data to Tableau Desktop to create a visualization:

Plotting

Now you’ve got a tidy structure, it’s time for some exploratory data analysis!

Plot the total number of housing units built in B.C. by municipality, but only the 10 municipalities with the greatest number of homes built, sorted from most to least. (I will leave it up to you to decide if you want to do that by a single year or by the total of all three years in the data.)

homes_chart <- new_homes_bc %>%  
  filter(year %in% c("2016", "2017", "2018")) %>%
  group_by(community) %>% 
  summarise(total = sum(multi, na.rm= TRUE, rental, na.rm= TRUE, single, na.rm= TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(total)) %>%
  slice(1:10) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = reorder(community, -total), y = total))

homes_chart +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Municipalities in B.C. with Highest Number of New Houses",
       subtitle = "2016-2018",
       caption = "Source: B.C. Ministry of Municipal Affairs and Housing",
       y = "Total New Houses",
       x = NULL)

Because some of the municipalities labels are overlapping, we can swap the axes:

homes_chart2 <- new_homes_bc %>%  
  filter(year %in% c("2016", "2017", "2018")) %>%
  group_by(community) %>% 
  summarise(total = sum(multi, na.rm= TRUE, rental, na.rm= TRUE, single, na.rm= TRUE)) %>% 
  arrange(desc(total)) %>%
  slice(1:10) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(aes(x = total, y = reorder(community, -total)))

homes_chart2 +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Municipalities in B.C. with Highest Number of New Houses",
       subtitle = "2016-2018",
       caption = "Source: B.C. Ministry of Municipal Affairs and Housing",
       y = "Total New Houses",
       x = NULL)
